liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan thanked the emergency service crews, including volunteers, who have been working in the state's east and north-east. "They started the week working on fires. Some of that fire activity continues and now in the later end of the week they are working on the flood response," she said. She said after flood levels peak, which is expected to occur around midday, teams would be better placed to assess any damage. "Teams will then be able to go in and assess the level of inundation, particularly in homes," she said. "They've not been able to get in and do that assessment yet because the floodwaters continue to rise and a number of roads remain closed in the local community." The premier said the release of water at Lake Glenmaggie and Lake Eildon had been discussed at an emergency meeting last night. She said nine people had spent the night at the relief centre at Sale, and that that personal hardship payments were available for those affected by the floods. "I want to thank local communities and local residents for heeding the warnings and making their decisions early as to how they can make themselves and their families safe in this emergency situation," Ms Allan said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Premier says flood damage will be assessed after levels  peak

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Daniel Miles Southern Rural Water has responded to criticism it didn’t react quickly enough to forecast flooding in East Gippsland. Newry dairy farmer Steve Dwyer, whose property is impacted by the floods, told ABC Victorian Mornings that the peak water body should have released water from the Glenmaggie Weir earlier. “No attempt was made to drop the level of the ‘Maggie’ weir,” he says. The ABC understands water releases from Lake Glenmaggie reached 58,000 megalitres overnight. Southern Rural Water has defended its actions, stating it worked to the information available at the time. “We ran models before the events over the last couple of days and those models were based on the high end of the rainfall range in this catchment,” managing director Cameron Fitzgerald says. “The models aren't wrong, we use the best available information that we have. “And then of course, there are variations in what actually happens, where the rain falls in the particular catchment, and how that flows. He stopped short of apologising to residents, stating welfare’s been at the forefront of all decisions. “We have managed the dam in a way that has taken the peak off this flood,” Mr Fitzgerald says. “Unquestionably the dam being there has reduced the amount of flooding downstream.”
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Water authority defends Lake Glenmaggie management

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The federal government has condemned racist abuse being directed toward independent senator Lidia Thorpe by far-right extremists. It comes after a video was published online in the last week by a masked neo nazi, who referred to Senator Thorpe by name before burning the Aboriginal flag and performing a nazi salute. Home Affairs Minister Clare O'Neil says Australian Federal Police are investigating the matter, but declined to discuss the details of AFP actions. "The Australian government takes this sort of thing incredibly seriously," she told Channel 9 this morning. "No one in our country deserves to be treated that way, but certainly not someone who is representing her community in federal parliament. "It is absolutely appalling, disgusting and the Australian government will be doing everything that we can to support Senator Thorpe through what must be an absolutely terrifying experience for her." Labor frontbencher Bill Shorten also condemned the video as "cowardly and gutless". "It's cowardly and disgusting, I don't know what it is with these man-baby nazis, wearing a hood so no one can see you, they think they're so tough," he told Channel 9. "Sending it and trying to pressure one of our senators and abuse them, I think it's cowardly and gutless and I just wish that bloke would take his hood off so people can see what sort of real joker he is." Senator Thorpe will be holding a press conference later today to make a statement on the threats of racist violence and intimidation against her.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Kimberley Price Former prime minister Tony Abbott was one of the earliest and staunchest opponents of an Indigenous Voice to Parliament and spoke to RN Breakfast this morning. "This Voice is wrong in principle, and it will be bad in practice," he told host Patricia Karvelas. "Not only does it entrench race in our constitution, it'll gum up our governmental systems even more. "Perhaps even worse, it'll further entrench this separatism which has bedevilled Aboriginal policy really since the days of Gough Whitlam." Mr Abbott says First Nations people "should be encouraged to integrate into the mainstream of our society". He reinforced prominent No campaigner Warren Mundine's sentiments that "the best thing any Australian can do" is go to school, get a job, buy a home if you can, get married and have a family to have a good life. "Unfortunately, too often, policy has encouraged Aboriginal people to stay, if you like, at arm's length from the rest of Australia and to operate at somewhat different standards," Mr Abbott said. "This is why in remote Australia where the problems are most acute, you've got the kids not going to school, adults not going to work, and the ordinary law of the land not always being properly enforced." Mr Abbott says the Voice to Parliament referendum is about inequality and deserves to fail. He will be speaking at a community event organised by the No campaign in the New South Wales Hunter region tonight.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Tony Abbott says Voice referendum is about inequality and deserves to fail
